<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-13T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-13T16:00:00-05:00" n="752" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d752">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/1308</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Spam</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Willard</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-13T17:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 13, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1423. Referring further your cable of July 31, 11 a.m., Embassy’s
                                    1608,<note n="1" xml:id="d752fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1691">p.
                                        1691</ref>.</note> also your cable of August 2, 6 p.m.,
                                Embassy’s 1631,<note n="2" xml:id="d752fn2">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1692">p.
                                        1692</ref>.</note> duly received.</p>
                            <p>We believe any agreement you can make at fixed rates of freight for
                                Spanish tonnage, basis of third proposition, will be acceptable. We,
                                of course, prefer time charter first; second, lump-sum charter, by
                                which they give us the full capacity of the vessel for respective
                                voyages; third, the basis of rates on cargo, weight or measurement
                                varying according to destinations, Italy, French Mediterranean or
                                French Atlantic ports. Any block of tonnage you may secure would be
                                acceptable. The British have asked us to allow the <hi rend="italic">Serantes, Gloria</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">Carasa</hi> to
                                remain on the other side for the ore trade, but we will not consent
                                until we hear from you as to whether this will interfere with your
                                negotiations.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>